<li><strong>Davenport</strong> — Short-term rental hotspot near Disney. Different investment model — higher revenue potential but more management, seasonal fluctuation, and regulatory risk.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Hernando, Manatee, Sarasota, Citrus</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong><a href="/counties/hernando/">Hernando County</a></strong> — Ultra-affordable acquisitions ($220K–$350K) with rents of $1,400–$1,800. Best for cash flow investors who don't mind managing from a distance. Tenant quality and vacancy are the risks.</li>
<li><strong><a href="/counties/manatee/">Manatee County</a></strong> — <a href="/cities/bradenton/">Bradenton</a> and <a href="/cities/parrish/">Parrish</a> offer solid rental demand. <a href="/cities/lakewood-ranch/">Lakewood Ranch</a> rents are high but acquisition costs are also high, compressing cap rates.</li>
<li><strong><a href="/counties/sarasota/">Sarasota County</a></strong> — <a href="/cities/north-port/">North Port</a> is the investor play — affordable new construction with growing demand. <a href="/cities/sarasota/">Sarasota</a> proper and the keys are appreciation plays, not cash flow.</li>
<li><strong><a href="/counties/citrus/">Citrus County</a></strong> — Lowest prices in the metro. Best for experienced investors who can manage higher vacancy and maintenance needs.</li>
</ul>
